{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474688"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:23:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12279"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12279"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.69,0.05,0.01,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81567"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4801"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66922"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"375"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1194"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44876"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81567"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department after being hit on the left side of his head by a cricket ball. His teacher reports he initially collapsed to the ground and complained of headache. After two minutes, he got up, said he felt fine and continued playing. Thirty minutes later, he suddenly collapsed again and became confused. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 59/min, blood pressure 145/94 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min irregular, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Scale score is 11/15 (E3 V3 M5). There is tenderness over the left temporoparietal region. He has right-sided hemiparesis and an upgoing right plantar response.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subarachnoid haemorrhage","Extradural haematoma","Intracerebral haemorrhage","Intraventricular haemorrhage","Subdural haematoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad for \u003Cstrong\u003Eextradural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E: initial loss of consciousness, lucid interval, and subsequent deterioration. The location of impact over the temporoparietal region is typical, as injury here often tears the middle meningeal artery. The rapid accumulation of blood between the dura and skull causes progressive neurological deterioration and the lucid interval. The presence of Cushing\u0027s triad (bradycardia, hypertension, and irregular breathing) indicates raised intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubdural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with progressive deterioration from the time of injury without a lucid interval. It occurs when bridging veins tear between the brain surface and dural venous sinuses, with blood collecting between the dura and arachnoid layers. It is more common in elderly patients or those with coagulopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracerebral haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E usually occurs in the context of hypertension or underlying vascular abnormalities rather than trauma. When traumatic, it is associated with severe impact or penetrating injury. There is no lucid interval, and patients present with sudden alteration in consciousness and focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with thunderclap headache and meningism. While it can be traumatic, it is more commonly due to ruptured aneurysm. The onset is sudden without a lucid interval, and patients typically have a severe headache as the predominant symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraventricular haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E is uncommon as a primary traumatic event, usually occurring as an extension of other intracranial bleeding. It presents with rapid onset of hydrocephalus and decreased consciousness without a lucid interval. Focal neurological signs are typically minimal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A lucid interval followed by deterioration is pathognomonic of extradural haematoma.","Extradural haematoma typically occurs after trauma to the temporoparietal region causing middle meningeal artery injury.","Cushing\u0027s triad (bradycardia, hypertension, irregular breathing) indicates raised intracranial pressure."],"references":["Guo C, Liu L, Wang B, Wang Z. Swirl sign in traumatic acute epidural hematoma: prognostic value and surgical management. Neurol Sci. 2017 Dec. 38 (12):2111-2116.","Vella MA, Crandall ML, Patel MB. Acute Management of Traumatic Brain Injury. Surg Clin North Am. 2017 Oct;97(5):1015-1030."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66922"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12279"}},"st